Explanation:

I inspected the web and API controllers and the route definitions for DELETE /posts/{post}/likes:

- routes/auth.php registers a web route (under auth middleware) for DELETE /posts/{post}/likes handled by App\Http\Controllers\PostLikeController::destroy. That controller returns a MultiplePendingTurboStreamResponse built from two turbo-stream actions: one that replaces the DOM element identified by dom_id($post, 'like') and one that updates dom_id($post, 'likes_count') with the current likes count. That corresponds to an HTML turbo-stream response (media type typically text/vnd.turbo-stream.html) with turbo-stream XML payload containing two <turbo-stream> elements.

- routes/api.php registers an API route (under auth:sanctum, verified) for DELETE /api/v1/posts/{post}/likes handled by App\Http\Controllers\Api\V1\PostLikeController::destroy. That controller returns the result of $post->dislike(). The Likeable::dislike method deletes likes and returns the collection of deleted Like models; when returned from an API controller Laravel will serialize that collection to JSON (an array of Like objects with fields such as id, likeable_id, likeable_type, author_id, created_at, updated_at).

Considering both routes, the DELETE operation may respond with:
- 200 OK with a Turbo Stream XML payload for the web route (text/vnd.turbo-stream.html).
- 200 OK with an application/json payload (array of deleted Like objects) for the API route.
Also possible error responses:
- 401 Unauthorized / Unauthenticated when the user is not authenticated (middleware).
- 404 Not Found when the Post resource is not found.

